         <TR BGCOLOR="#6A6144"><Td ALIGN="LEFT">
         <FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana" COLOR="white">
         <blockquote>
         Sorcerer's are on-demand casters. They don't have all the spells of a wizard, so are limited in what they can do. If they concentrate on damage spells, then clearly rogues will be better suited towards them because of their reflex saves.<P>However, a wizard can recognize that his opponent is a rogue, and switch tactics accordingly, concentrated on maximized unsavable spells, will spells, disablers, or fortitude kill shots. My wizard prepares several avenues of attack, but unlike a sorcerer, if that avenue of attack fails to affect my opponent in the desired way, then I can't attempt it over again and am stuck with whatever else I've prepared. I can't sit there and memorize 5 Finger of Death's because I've got a 10% chance of landing one, I've got to diversify so I can get more of a guarantee on my win.<P>The only two classes I've seen good at reflex saves are rogues (plus their dex bonus) and monks (who's saves are all high by default). <P>By the way, I've built a wizard with 300 hit points and immune to death magic. With buff spells and damage reduction spells, he stands up to barbarians (and their 400 hp) quite welll, especially since they can't dispel that well. DSO PvP is a situation where you've got to understand the nature of your opponent, and then find out what feats/spells can beat him. Problem is, people are lazy. They spend this time to get a character to 20, only to realize half the game has built a better character, and he's shit outta luck because he can't compete at the top level. <P>I still think you should stop bitching and adapt. ;) After the things you've said, it's clear that you've not tested at the length we have, considering that the equipment in the game is a deciding factor. Ok, so you know a rogue or a monk is gonna be practically immune to elemental spells... so, use something else! There's 4 avenues of attack on a person: Fort spells, Will spells, Reflex spells, and Melee.<P>Oh, mords disjunction drops spell resistance by 10 each cast. Their spell resist is 30 at level 20, which means that a mage of 20th level must roll a 1d20   20 (their spell level) and beat that 30. One mords disjuction drops all spell resistance on a monk. Now you gotta deal with impossible saves, unlimited healing kits, and 6 attacks a round... know what to do next? I do, and it's gonna be a cookie cutter technique to beat monks every time until they change their tactics.<P>Know what the monk can do in his defense? I do, and I'd use it on every mage everytime until they change their tactics or build a better character.<P>Adapt, overcome, prevail. DSO PvP is balanced, and will continue to be balanced as time goes on so that no one is invincible unless it's strictly by skill.
         </blockquote>
